<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Geoff Dawson – Written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Geoff Dawson – Written evidence </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">My concern is with the state of the Green Lanes that I constantly see being destroyed by motorised vehicles, 4x4s and trials bikes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I remember one occasion when I went caving on Fountains Fell in the Yorkshire Dales. On the way to the cave, we walked along a perfect grassy track. On the way back, 2 recreational 4x4’s approached and past us. Just the 2 of them, but they reduced the track to a quagmire in a single pass. Two peoples’ moment of fun destroyed the track for everyone for the next year!</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I would like to make two proposals</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that all unsealed Byways Open to All Traffic (BOATS), and all unsealed Unclassified County Roads (UCRs) should by recognised as not being part of the ordinary roads network, and should be reclassified as Restricted Byways.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">When a local authority declines to impose a traffic regulation order that is widely-supported by the public, there should be a right of appeal, either to an </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">independent  inspector</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, or a magistrate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These proposals are covered in more detail by the formal submissions made by the Green Lanes Environmental Action Group(GLEAM), the Green Lanes Protection Group (GLPG), the Peak District Green Lanes Alliance (PDGLA)  and the Yorkshire Dales Green Lanes Alliance (YDGLA) which I expressly support.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>